Step 1:
Create a max heap.

The max heap will keep the farthest point at the top.

Step 2:
For every point in points:

    Add the point into the heap.

Step 3:
If heap size becomes greater than k:

    Remove the top point from the heap.

Because the top point is the farthest point.

Step 4:
After checking all points, the heap will contain only k closest points.

Step 5:
Create a result array of size k.

Step 6:
Remove all points from the heap and store them in result.

Step 7:
Return result.

Code:
class Solution {
    public int[][] kClosest(int[][] points, int k) {

        PriorityQueue<int[]> maxHeap = new PriorityQueue<>(
            (a,b) -> Integer.compare( b[0]*b[0] + b[1]*b[1], a[0]*a[0]+a[1]*a[1]));

        for(int[] point : points)
        {
            maxHeap.add(point);
            if(maxHeap.size() > k)
            {
                maxHeap.poll();
            }
        }


        int[][] result = new int[k][2];

        for(int i =0; i<k;i++)
        {
            result[i] = maxHeap.poll();
        }

        return result;
        
    }
}
